Topic 1: Version Control

Introduction

Version control is a critical part of any collaborative data science and engineering project. It ensures that changes to code, models, and data are tracked, enables collaborative workflows, and provides a safety net to roll back changes when necessary. This section outlines best practices for using Git effectively.

1. Git Workflow and Branching Strategies

	•	Branch Types:
	1.	Main (or main): The stable branch representing the production-ready state of the project.
	2.	Development (or develop): The active branch where ongoing development occurs.
	3.	Feature Branches: Used for implementing new features (e.g., feature/v3_model_training).
	4.	Bugfix Branches: For fixing specific bugs in the codebase (e.g., bugfix/issue_123).
	5.	Hotfix Branches: For urgent fixes applied directly to production (e.g., hotfix/critical_fix).
	6.	Release Branches: For final testing and polishing before merging to main (e.g., release/v3.0).
	•	Branching Strategy:
	•	Gitflow: Use a branching strategy like Gitflow for structured development:
	•	main: Production-ready branch.
	•	develop: Active development branch.
	•	feature/*: New features branch from develop.
	•	bugfix/*: Bug fixes branch from develop.
	•	hotfix/*: Critical fixes branch directly from main and merge back into main and develop.
	•	release/*: Branch from develop for preparing releases.

2. Commit Message Conventions

Use clear and consistent commit messages to improve collaboration and code readability. Adopt this format for commit messages:
	•	Structure:

[type]: Brief summary of the change

	•	Types:
	•	feat: A new feature (e.g., feat: add v3 model retraining pipeline).
	•	fix: A bug fix (e.g., fix: correct data type issue in training dataset).
	•	docs: Documentation changes (e.g., docs: update README for v3 model).
	•	style: Code style changes (e.g., style: reformat code for consistency).
	•	refactor: Code restructuring (e.g., refactor: optimize feature engineering pipeline).
	•	test: Adding or modifying tests (e.g., test: add unit tests for API endpoints).

3. Commit Best Practices

	•	Keep Commits Atomic: Each commit should represent one logical change (e.g., “add preprocessing step”).
	•	Write Descriptive Messages: Avoid vague messages like “fixed bug.”
	•	Avoid Large Commits: Break down large changes into smaller, manageable commits.

4. Tagging and Versioning

Tags provide snapshots of the repository for releases or milestones.
	•	Tagging Syntax: Use semantic versioning (vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH):
	•	v1.0.0: Initial release.
	•	v1.1.0: Minor update or new feature.
	•	v1.1.1: Patch for a bug fix.
	•	Example: Tag a release with git tag -a v1.0.0 -m "First stable release".

5. Pull Requests and Code Reviews

	•	Use Pull Requests for Changes:
	•	Create a pull request (PR) for every feature or bugfix branch.
	•	Include a clear description of the change and why it’s needed.
	•	Code Review Checklist:
	•	Does the code follow style guidelines?
	•	Is the logic clear and maintainable?
	•	Are there adequate comments and documentation?
	•	Do the tests cover the new functionality?

6. Merging Strategies

	•	Use merge or rebase:
	•	Merge for larger changes, preserving branch history.
	•	Rebase for smaller, linear histories.
	•	Best Practices:
	•	Always ensure the branch is up-to-date with main or develop before merging.
	•	Resolve conflicts locally and test thoroughly.

7. Git Commands Reference

Command	Purpose
git init	Initialize a new Git repository
git clone <repo>	Clone an existing repository
git checkout -b <branch>	Create and switch to a new branch
git add <file>	Stage changes
git commit -m "<msg>"	Commit staged changes with a message
git push origin <branch>	Push changes to a remote repository
git pull	Fetch and merge changes from the remote
git tag -a <tag>	Create an annotated tag
git merge <branch>	Merge changes from one branch to another

8. Example Workflow

	1.	Create a feature branch for a new model:

git checkout -b feature/v3_model_training


	2.	Make and commit changes:

git add .
git commit -m "feat: add v3 training pipeline"


	3.	Push changes and create a pull request:

git push origin feature/v3_model_training


	4.	Review and merge the PR into develop.

