Branching Strategy for Collaborative Projects

Effective branching strategies are essential for teams working on multiple tasks within the same repository, especially when tasks are interdependent. Here are detailed guidelines for organizing branches when multiple people are collaborating:

1. Branch Types

Your branching strategy should include the following types:
	1.	Main Branch (main):
	•	The stable branch containing production-ready code.
	•	Only merge tested and reviewed changes into main.
	2.	Develop Branch (develop):
	•	The integration branch where features and tasks are merged.
	•	Serves as the base for all feature branches.
	•	This branch is tested regularly but is not considered production-ready.
	3.	Feature Branches (feature/*):
	•	Used to develop individual features or large tasks.
	•	Each feature branch focuses on one functionality or independent task.
	•	Naming convention: feature/<task_name> (e.g., feature/data_cleaning, feature/model_training).
	4.	Task Branches (task/*):
	•	Sub-branches of feature branches for specific smaller tasks within a larger feature.
	•	Useful when a single feature involves multiple contributors.
	•	Naming convention: task/<feature_name>/<sub_task> (e.g., task/data_cleaning/missing_values).
	5.	Report Branches (report/*):
	•	Dedicated branches for writing specific sections of a report or conducting analyses for the report.
	•	Naming convention: report/<section> (e.g., report/eda_summary, report/model_performance).
	6.	Bugfix Branches (bugfix/*):
	•	For resolving bugs found in develop or main.
	•	Naming convention: bugfix/<issue_description> (e.g., bugfix/fix-null-values).
	7.	Hotfix Branches (hotfix/*):
	•	For urgent fixes in production (main branch).
	•	Naming convention: hotfix/<issue_description> (e.g., hotfix/api-timeout-error).
	8.	Release Branches (release/*):
	•	Temporary branches created for final testing before merging into main.
	•	Naming convention: release/<version> (e.g., release/v3.0).

2. How Many Feature Branches to Create?

The number of feature branches depends on the size of the project, the number of contributors, and the independence of tasks. Here are some guidelines:

When Tasks Are Independent:

	•	One Feature Branch Per Task:
	•	Example: If three people are working on data cleaning, model training, and exploratory data analysis, create:
	•	feature/data_cleaning
	•	feature/model_training
	•	feature/eda
	•	Assign each contributor to their respective feature branch.

When Tasks Are Interdependent:

	•	Create a Shared Feature Branch with Task Sub-Branches:
	•	Example: If multiple people are working on preprocessing (e.g., handling missing values, scaling, and encoding):
	•	Create a shared feature/data_preprocessing branch.
	•	Create task branches:
	•	task/data_preprocessing/missing_values
	•	task/data_preprocessing/scaling
	•	task/data_preprocessing/encoding

When Reports Require Collaboration:

	•	Create Separate Report Branches for Each Section:
	•	Example: If one person is working on EDA results and another on model performance:
	•	report/eda_summary
	•	report/model_performance
	•	Merge these branches into a shared report branch regularly.

3. Key Practices for Managing Multiple Feature Branches

A. Synchronize Regularly

	•	Pull Changes Daily: Ensure that everyone pulls changes from the parent branch (develop) to avoid large merge conflicts later.
	•	Merge into develop Frequently: Feature branches should not grow too large. Merge regularly to integrate progress.

B. Minimize Dependency Risks

	•	For dependent tasks, plan task order and branch relationships in advance.
	•	Example: Preprocessing tasks must be completed before training begins.
	•	Merge preprocessing results into develop before starting model training.

C. Avoid Overlap in Work

	•	Assign clear responsibilities for each branch. If tasks overlap, discuss how to divide work to prevent conflicts.

D. Test Before Merging

	•	Test your feature branch locally or with automated tests before merging into develop.

E. Use Tags for Milestones

	•	Tag key points in the workflow to allow easy reference (e.g., v1.0-preprocessing-complete).

4. Example Branching Plan

Scenario:

Five team members are working on the following tasks for a model training project:
	1.	Data cleaning (Person A)
	2.	Exploratory analysis (Person B)
	3.	Feature engineering (Person C)
	4.	Model training (Person D)
	5.	Report writing (Person E)

Proposed Branching Strategy:

	•	main: Stable production-ready branch.
	•	develop: Integration branch.
	•	Feature branches:
	•	feature/data_cleaning (Person A)
	•	feature/eda (Person B)
	•	feature/feature_engineering (Person C)
	•	feature/model_training (Person D)
	•	feature/report (Person E)
	•	Task branches (if needed):
	•	task/feature_engineering/interaction_terms (Person C)
	•	task/feature_engineering/polynomial_features (Person C)
	•	task/report/model_performance (Person E)
	•	PR Reviews:
	•	Assign one reviewer for each feature branch.
	•	Example: Person C reviews Person A’s PR for feature/data_cleaning.

5. PR Review and Conflict Resolution

PR Review Guidelines:

	1.	Test Your Code: Ensure your branch runs without errors before submitting a PR.
	2.	Review Checklist:
	•	Is the code style consistent?
	•	Does the code address the task described?
	•	Are all tests passing?

Conflict Resolution:

	•	Early Synchronization: Pull and merge changes regularly to reduce the chance of conflicts.
	•	Resolve Locally:
	•	Use git merge or git rebase to handle conflicts.
	•	Test thoroughly before pushing changes.

